pdc_describe.title: Validate cytoskeletal xml datacite schema
Clean out PDC Describe Production to prep for data migration
Validate XML produced by migration specs
Ensure quotations in Datacite xml are encoded correctly

comments.body:
@Twade968 : I don't think this is a problem: I think the screen shot you've taken is from the XML? Character encoding is used in XML to prevent conflicts with the XML syntax itself, for example `>` and `<`, but it can also be used even if there isn't a conflict, as is the case here.

To confirm that things are ok, I added a breakpoint in the test and looked at the data:
```
(byebug) doc = REXML::Document.new(datacite.to_xml)
(byebug) REXML::XPath.first(doc, "//description").text.split("\n").select { |line| line.include? "thesis work" }
["      To address this, Christina Karas's thesis work focuses on developing"]
```
When we get the data out of the XML, the entities are decoded.

Suggest closing, or clarifying the issue.

@mccalluc Good point! This was based on feedback we got from folks reviewing the XML records for migration, and I encouraged Tyler to open this ticket. If it comes up again I'll remind everyone (including myself!) that these characters SHOULD be encoded like this in an XML record. 

I will close this issue.

comments.body:
I suspect that the resources were all created and marked complete, but with private visibility. At that point, the UpdateDaoJob would have run:
https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/blob/d7d7e9bc945a4c96d483d7e6d1cc173f9fcd6c5a/app/change_set_persisters/change_set_persister/update_aspace_dao.rb#L10-L14

But not done anything:
https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/blob/d7d7e9bc945a4c96d483d7e6d1cc173f9fcd6c5a/app/services/dao_updater.rb#L11-L12

According to this theory, when they were later made public (and we do see a BulkUpdateJob from Nov 29th making them public), they were not "recently published" at that point, so the UpdateDaoJob wasn't run at all.

Question: Is there any reason we can't just check for a public readable state and not check for the state change? I.e. Is it bad to run that job multiple times?
